Become a contributor
Once the local environment is set up, there are 2 GitHub repositories available to contribute to:

Contribute to the widgets and themes repository

1. On GitHub.com, navigate to the People-Places-Solutions/experience-builder-widget-themes repository.

2. In the top-right corner of the page, click Fork. On the next page, keep the default settings and click Create Fork.

3. In the ./client directory of your local environment, use git clone https://github.com/[your-username]/experience-builder-widget-theme custom-widgets-themes to clone the forked repo.

4. Within the repo, any custom widgets must live within a widgets child directory. Similarly, any custom themes must live within a themes child directory. Webpack will compile the widgets automatically when executing npm start . Happy developing!

5. When ready to propose a new widget or theme, submit a pull request into the upstream GitHub repository from Step 1.

Contribute to the apps and templates repository

1. On GitHub.com, navigate to the People-Places-Solutions/experience-builder-apps repository.

2. In the top-right corner of the page, click Fork. On the next page, keep the default settings and click Create Fork.

3. In the ./server/public directory of your local environment, use git clone https://github.com/[your-username]/experience-builder-apps.git apps to clone the forked repo.

4. If an ./server/apps/ directory exists, it must be renamed to something other than "apps" or removed. The app configurations will compile when executing npm start . Happy developing!

5. When ready to propose a new app or template, submit a pull request into the upstream GitHub repository from Step 1.
Host custom widgets for ArcGIS Enterprise 11x

When a widget is finished being developed, it can be used within the local development environment or it can be added to a portal for others to use. Follow the steps below to host the custom widget in GitHub.
Deploy app to GitHub

Download the experience

1. Go to the experience gallery home page in the local environment.

2. Click on the ellipsis for the experience and click Download. A ZIP file is created and downloaded to the local drive.

Once the local environment is set up, daily start up steps are the following:

1. In the /server directory, run npm start to start the server.

2. In the /client directory, run npm start to start the service.

3. Open Experience Builder at the following url https://localhost:3001/ in the browser.

4. Sign in with the URL to your ArcGIS Online organization or ArcGIS Enterprise and the Client ID for Experience Builder.

Deploy the experience in GitHub

1. Create a new repository in GitHub for the project.

2. In the repository's Code tab, click Add file > Upload files. Unzip the downloaded experience and add the contents of the folder. Then commit the changes.

3. Once it finishes building and deploying, navigate to the Settings tab > Code and automation section > Pages. In the branch dropdown select main then click Save.

4. Refresh the page and there will be a new box at the top with a url of where the app is deployed.

5. If your app has private content, continue with the next section to ensure the app can access the content.

Add and register apps with private content

1. Go to ArcGIS Online or ArcGIS Enterprise.

2. On the Content page, click New item. In the window, select Web mapping under Application type and enter the deployed url. Click Next.

3. Fill out the item details and click Save.

4. Go to the new Web Mapping Application item's Settings page. Under the Web Mapping Application section, copy the Client ID.

5. In the project's GitHub repository, navigate to ./cdn/<app name>/config.json and click the pencil icon in the top right to edit the file.

6. Create a clientId property under the attributes object and paste the Client ID from Step 4 here as a string.

7. Commit the changes. Once it finishes building and deploying, there will be a login prompt when the app is launched.

8. If there are any issues, try clearing the browser's cache and reload the page.


See detailed documentation here.

Compile the widget

1. First, you need to compile the widget. To do this run npm run build:prod in the /client directory.

2. The compiled widget shows up in the /client/dist-prod-widgets directory.

Deploy the widget in GitHub

1. Go to the geospatial-developer-platform GitHub repository.

2. In the Code tab, navigate to the appropriate version folder under exb_widgets.

3. You can find the widget version in the manifest.json.

4. Click Add file > Upload files.

5. Add the entire widget folder from the client/dist-prod/widgets directory. Commit the changes.

Log the widget

1. Use the editor on the right to log the widget details.

2. Logged widgets show up in the Widget Library.


To add the custom widget to a portal, see Add a custom widget to Enterprise.
*It is required to have portal administrator privileges to register a custom widget.
Go to the Widget Library to find a custom widget's URL path.
